 or Norwegian origin."]},{"name":"Knudsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Knud, Niels, Holger, Jorgen, Ove, Alf, Alfhild, Anders, Baard, Berger, Einer.","Danish, Norwegian, and North German: patronymic from the Danish personal name <i>Knud</i>, derived from Old Norse <i>Knútr</i> meaning ‘knot’. <i>Knud</i> was a Danish royal name, Latinized as <i>Canutus</i>."]}]},{"name":"Lars","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Laurence</b> ; one of the most perennially popular names in Sweden and Denmark."],"variants":[{"name":"Laurence","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lars Knutson was born about 1370, in Sweden. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Lars Ragvaldsdotter Knutson. He died after 1410."},"et":{"about 1370–after 1410":"umbes 1370–pärast 1410","1370–1410":"1370–1410","1410–1430":"1410–1430","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1370":"1370","after 1410":"pärast 1410","Sweden":"Rootsi","Floda, Södermanland, Sweden":"Floda, Södermanland, Rootsi"},"fi":{"about 1370–after 1410":"noin 137